@REM==============================================================================

@node "PreRelease" "Pre-Release Informations"

                            @{b}Pre-Release Informations
                           ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

FAME is a brand new MailBox program which seems to become very popular
and FAMEous as we can see on the very positive reactions we receive
daily.

We already have many bug-reports and suggestions and we beleave we will
get tones more from the very first release on.

We work hard on fixing all reported bugs and realize suggestions as best we
can, but it's impossible to do all at the same time.

The same with the documents.
The documents are not complete at all... we have to enhance and anlarge
the documents as long as we have to do this with the FAME executables.

You have bought FAME in an early stage and because of this not everything
written here must be 100% correct but we work on it.


@{u}@{b}Known not described parts in FAME.guide@{uu}@{ub}

 - None.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "Contents" "FAME Amigaguide Document - FAME Server Contents"

                         @{b}FAME SERVER DOCUMENT CONTENTS
                        ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

 @{b}@{u}Introduction@{ub}@{uu}

 The Server is the controlling center of FAME, without it the FAME BBS won't
 work ! The Server manages the controlling of FAME and the nodes, allows to
 execute Programs on specific actions of FAME and also gives you a quick
 overview what currently happen in your BBS when users are online.

 The Server is a commodity, so it could be controlled via ExChange or other
 similiar programs. Also all other features a commodity have are available,
 like it's own definable PopUp-Hotkey for the Server.

 This documentation describes how to install, configure and use the Server.
 Also this documentation can be used as an Online-Manual to give you help
 when you press the HELP-Key over a gadget on the Server.

 @{b}@{u}Contents of this documentation@{ub}@{uu}

 @{"   TOOLTYPES   " link "TOOLTYPES" 0} - Describes the Start and the Tooltypes/Shell arguments
 @{" CONFIGURATION " link "CONFIGURATION" 0} - How to configure the System- and Userbuttons
 @{" SERVER WINDOW " link "MAIN_WINDOW" 0} - Complete description of the Server Window and Buttons

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "TOOLTYPES" "How to start the Server/List of Tooltypes & Shell args"

                          @{u}How to start the Server@{uu}

 The Server could be started from Workbench or CLI, but the CLI-Start should
 only be used for debugging purposes, because the Server writes all actions
 in the Shell window it was started from. This is only useful, if you i.e.
 have an unknown error and you need to know exactly whats happend. If you
 start the Server from CLI, the only Argument the Server accepts is the
 @{fg shine}IDLE/S@{fg text} option, this starts the Server but doesn't start the nodes.
 This Option is also available as a ToolType.

 When starting the Server from Workbench, some of the standard commodity
 tooltypes and also some own tooltypes are available, but with the exception
 of the @{fg shine}BBSLOCATION@{fg text} Tooltype they are not required for the Server to work.
 All Server related settings are also configurable in the @{"SystemEditor" link "SystemEditor.guide/Main"} under
 Server Settings. Refer to the @{"SystemEditor" link "SystemEditor.guide/Main"} manual for further informations
 on those settings.

 @{b}List of all currently supported tooltypes:@{ub}

 BBSLOCATION=FAME:       @{b}->@{ub} This Tooltype is the only important ToolType for
                            the Server, without this it won't start! Here
                            you must specify the main location of FAME,
                            which by default is set to the Assign FAME:

 CX_POPUP=<YES|NO>       @{b}->@{ub} Set it to YES to let the Server open it's window
                            when starting. If set to NO, the Server starts
                            iconified. This Tooltype will be overridden if
                            you have specified the Iconify Option in the
                            SystemEditor/Server Settings.

 CX_PRIORITY=0           @{b}->@{ub} Specifies the Priority for the Server. Normally
                            this is set to 0. This Tooltype will be over-
                            written if you have specified the Priority in
                            the SystemEditor/Server Settings.

 CX_POPKEY=alt f         @{b}->@{ub} Here you may specify a hotkey to open the Server
                            window without double-clicking on it's App-Icon
                            first.

 IDLE                    @{b}->@{ub} If this Tooltype is present, the Server will
                            be started without starting the nodes.

 The following Tooltypes only take affect when starting the Server from
 your SYS:WBStartup/ drawer. For detailed information about these and
 other Tooltypes for WBStartup Icons, please look in your Workbench Manual.

 DONOTWAIT               @{b}->@{ub} Necessary to let Workbench continue it's work
                            after starting Server. If you don't specify it,
                            WorkBench will wait until you have finished the
                            Server!

 STARTPRI=<PRIORITY>     @{b}->@{ub} Specifies the starting order of your WBStartup
                            programs. The priority defines which programs
                            are executed before others. The priority ranges
                            from -127 to +127, normally it is set to 0 if
                            not specified.

 WAIT=<SECS>             @{b}->@{ub} Defines the time in seconds the WBStartup-Loader
                            should wait before loading the next Program. 
                            This is useful for FAME, because the Server
                            loads in many datafiles at once, and other
                            programs which where started while loading the
                            datafiles could slow down the time the Server
                            needs to load in the datafiles. If you have a
                            SCSI-System or very fast HD's, it's not
                            necessary to use this Tooltype, but on slow HD's
                            or AT-Systems it could improve the Load-Time.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "CONFIGURATION" "How to configure the System- and Userbuttons"

                       @{u}CONFIGURATION OF THE SERVER@{uu}

 Some of the main-buttons are configurable, in addition there are @{i}28@{ui} user-
 definable buttons for your own purposes. All of the buttons are configured
 with the @{"SystemEditor" link "SystemEditor.guide/Main"}. For a complete description of all buttons from the
 Server, please refer to the Chapter @{"GUI-Description" link "MAIN_WINDOW" 0} in this document.

 @{b}Configuration of the System-Buttons:@{ub}

 The @{"system-buttons" link "BANKCYCLE" 0} of the Server contain calls to external FAME programs.
 The pathes for those programs are configurable in the @{fg fill}SystemEditor@{fg text} under
 the Section @{fg fill}FAME Modules@{fg text}. Please refer to the @{"SystemEditor" link "SystemEditor.guide/Main"} documentation
 for further information about the FAME Modules window.

 @{b}The following system-buttons of the Server are configurable:@{ub}

  UserEditor         @{b}->@{ub}  Used to start an external User-Editor, like the
                         MUI User-Editor contained in your FAME release.
                         Look in the @{"GUI-description" link "MAIN_WINDOW" 0} of this documentation
                         for further information.

  Info               @{b}->@{ub}  Used to start an external Info-command which shows
                         some values about the online user and his transfers


 @{b}Configuration of the User-Buttons:@{ub}

 In addition the the System-Buttons, also 28 freely-configurable buttons are
 available. To access them, switch the @{"System-Bank Cyclegadget" link "BANKCYCLE" 0} to the User-
 Bank 1 & 2 position. All User-Buttons are configurable in the @{fg fill}SystemEditor@{fg text}
 under Section @{fg fill}Server Settings@{fg text}. To configure your own buttons, follow these
 steps:

  @{b}1.@{ub} Select with the Cyclegadget if you want to configure a button for bank
     one or bank two.

  @{b}2.@{ub} Select the number of the button you want to change. Please note that
     all buttons are numbered from left to right, so button number one
     is the leftmost button, button two the one right after it etc. 

  @{b}3.@{ub} Now enter a name for the button. Make sure that the name is max. 10
     chars long, longer names are cut.

  @{b}4.@{ub} Finally enter the command line for this button to be executed. Here
     you should enter exactly the same line like when using this command
     via shell.

 @{b}Example for a User-Button (Bank 1/Button 1):@{ub}

 This example shows how to create a user-button called '@{fg shine}LASTCALLER@{fg text}' which
 should display the last callers to your BBS.

 Assuming that your LastCallers bulletin is called: @{fg shine}FAME:LastCallers.TXT@{fg text}
 and you have an ANSI-Textviewer called @{fg shine}BBS-View@{fg text} in C: , the configuration
 for this button should be:

 ButtonName: LastCaller
    Command: C:BBS-VIEW FAME:LASTCALLERS.TXT

 That's all! As you can see, it's not a problem to configure your own
 buttons inside the server.

@endnode

